1	Why do we have patient responsibility, even when the patient has Insurance coverage?	

Ans. In the US, generally the insurance payment ratio is always 80:20. This is to restrict the patients going to the doctors unnecessarily.
2	What is the difference between Copay and Coinsurance?	

Ans. Copay is the visiting charge, which the patient has to pay to the provider/provider's front office, for every visit, whereas Coinsurance is the percentage of the allowed amount, which the patient or the patient's secondary insurance pays, after the primary insurance's payment.

3	What is the difference between Medical and Dental?	

Ans. Medical focuses on curing and that is the reason it is called as curative care. On the other side, Dental focuses on prevention and it is called as preventive care.
4	What is the difference between Rejections and Denials?	

Ans. A claim rejection occurs before the claim is processed and most often results from incorrect/invalid data submitted to the insurance. Conversely, a claim denial applies to a claim that has been processed and found to be unpayable due to many factors, depending on the plan chosen by the patient.

5	Why do we have different codes for the Dental treatments?	

Ans. In Medical, we have diagnosis codes which indicate the nature of illness and procedure codes which indicate the treatment given by the provider to the patient. In Dental, there is no diagnosing done and that is why we do not have diagnosis codes in Dental billing. Instead we have diagnostic procedures, which is the combination of both diagnosis + procedure. The CDT code itself will be indicating both the patient's sickness and the provider's treatment.

6	Is Health Insurance in the US compulsory?	

Ans. Health Insurance in the US is not compulsory, however People there are forced to take health insurance policies, since the medical expenses in the US is expensive and people might not have money at the time of treatment.

7	Which is easy Medical or Dental?	

Ans. This depends on how you/trainees take. Whether it is Medical or Dental, the client and the software used is going to be different. However, the concepts followed is the same whether it is Medical or Dental.

8	Why do they have two different formats NSF and ANSI, both being electronic

do they have two different formats NSF and ANSI, both being electronic claims?	

Ans. Intially, we have one format NSF to send the claims electronically to the insurances. However, they found that the NSF had lot of restrictions and was consuming lot of space, due to which they were unable to send bulk claims at a time. Conversely, the ANSI had less restrictions and was consuming less space and they were able to send bulk claims at a time. Towrds the end, they found that ANSI was user-friendly and many started using the ANSI format to send the claims to the insurance.

9	Are the Electronic claims sent through e-mails?	

Ans. No, Electronic claims are sent through the highly protected billing softwares by the providers. Patient's health information is highly confidential and it cannot be shared with anybody. Moreover, sending the patient's personal and health details in e-mails is against HIPAA.

10	When the Claims are sent electronically, what is the possibility that the Claims are not hacked?	

Ans. When the claims are sent electronically, it does not reach the insurance as it is. The claims are encrypted into a different language so that, it cannot be hacked by anyone. However, it will be decrypted once it reaches the insurance adjudication system for them to process the claim.

11	Why the original x-rays are not shared with the patients, if requested?	

Ans. The dentist will have to maintain the patient's original x-rays for his/her repository and for the future references. However, if the patient's insurance or the patients requests the dentist for the same, the dentist can provide the digital copy of the x-ray with the patient or the patient's insurance.


12	Why there is no Dental Insurance in India and only in the US?	

Ans. People in the US are more health conscious than the people in India. They realized that Oral system is the base for every health issue and started Dental Insurance. Indians started realizing that and it is very evident from the number of new dental clinics popping-up in India nowadays.

13	Are Tax IDs and the SSN the same?	

Ans. No, Tax ID is given to all the tax payers or all who come under taxable income slab. However, SSN is the citizenship number given to every American for their social security benefits.

14	What is the difference between Inpatient and Outpatient?	

Ans. Inpatient is where, the patient stays in the hospital for more than 24 hours and get treatment. However, the outpatient is where the patient visits the hospital, gets the treatment and leaves on the same day.

15	Are we supposed to do Patient calling as well?	

Ans. That totally depends on your client. Some providers might give us both insurance and patient calling access. But some providers might not.


16	What is the need for the patients to take more than one insurance?	

Ans. If the patient feels that having one insurance is not sufficient to meet his/her and his/her family member's medical expenses, they can always go for extra one or two more insurances.

17	Why do we have separate policy for Railroad employees/retirees?	

Ans. Since the demand for Medicare grew high, the railroad employees were given the same benefits under RR Meidcare, once they retire. Therefore the rules and policy guidelines of Medicare and the RR Medicare is the same.

18	How does the patient know whether the provider is participating or not?	

Ans. The patient will come to know whether the provider is participating or not, while purchasing the insurance policy. The insurance will be giving them the list of providers for the patient to choose one provider from that list. The listed providers are called Participating and non-listed providers are called Non-participating.

19	Is Balance Billing and the Write-Off the same?	

Ans. No, Balance Billing is the patient's responsibility. When there is no contract signed between the insurance and the provider, the difference between the provider's billed amount and the insurance's allowed amount will have to be taken care by the patient. However, if the patient is not in a position to pay, out of professional courtesy, the provider can write-off the amount willingly from his/her side.

20	Why do they have separate benefits for Ophthalmology, when it is covered under Medical?	

Ans. Since the Uniformed Service Personnel are obligated to secure the country, their vision has to be perfect. Therefore, the US government has given them Ophthalmological benefits, though it is covered under Medical benefits.

22	Who can be a Guarantor - blood relatives or any friend?	

Ans. Guarantor need not necessarily be a relative/a family member of the patient. He/she should be the financial responsible person to pay the medical bills, if the patient fails to pay.

23	Why the Insurance payment ratio is 80:20?	

Ans. In the US, generally the insurance payment ratio is always 80:20 to restrict the patients going to the doctors unnecessarily and to make patients more responsible to use their insurance policy.

24	What is the difference between Fluoride and Sealants?	

Ans. Fluoride and Sealants are both preventive services. Fluoride is a chemical which strengthens our teeth enamel and helps the teeth to be decay resistant. Whereas, Sealant is an acrylic which is placed over the chewing/grinding surface of the posterior teeth, to protect the teeth from cavities, especially for children.

25	What is the difference between Fluoride and Fluoride Varnish?	

Ans. Fluoride is a chemical which strengthens our teeth enamel and helps the teeth to be decay resistant. Initially, with Fluoride foam, dental hygienists had to use a tray for application. With Fluoride Varnish, however, the tray is no longer necessary, and the Fluoride can be applied directly to the teeth - Fluoride Varnish is the upgraded version of Fluoride Tray application.

26	Does everyone on a specific group number, have the same benefits coverage?	

Ans. Yes, if everyone has the same group number, the benefits coverage will be the same. However, if they have a sub-group number as an extension to the group number, the benefits will definitely vary.

27	Does everyone from the same family have the same benefits?	

Ans. Yes, the benefits will remain the same for all the family members, since it is one policy.
